Incident Response > [T1]: Remote Incident Response: Challenges and Benefits

Where do we perform IR?

Most incident response activities are typically performed within the SOC. However, incident responders can perform their work and investigate incidents on-site or remotely. Under normal conditions, analysts go to their offices and work inside the SOC physical space. But the COVID-19 epidemic has changed how we behave and work. Many organizations started to adopt a remote work policy, and SOCs are no exception. For example, if you visit any job posting website, you will notice a higher demand for remote positions than the previous years. 

These are a few examples from the Indeed website: 


In the survey conducted by PwC on the status of remote jobs, SOC analysts found this remote work approach positive. 

According to SecurityIntelligence: 

"In June 2020, 73% of employees and employers rated remote work as positive in the PwC Remote Work Survey. A January 2021 survey of the same people found an increase of 10% to 83% positivity. In addition, in January 2021, 52% of employers reported they were more productive during remote work, up from 44% in June."

Adopting remote work introduced new risks that were not present before. End users share documents, chat, and need to access corporate servers and services from anywhere. The security team's job became even more challenging with the introduction of new technologies required for remote work, such as cloud platforms.

The other challenge introduced with remote work is broken communications. In the on-site model, all IR team members work harmoniously to sync attack details and actions, reducing response time and minimizing damage. Real contact is often effective during response and facilitates harmony and Sync between team members. These are things hard to maintain in a remote work model and require a great deal of security maturity, often available only to a few organizations that are well prepared on both the process and operational levels.

The relevant part for you is that most incident responders used to find the on-site shifts tough and stressful, preventing some newcomers from getting into a job in security. The good news is that situation is not present anymore, and remote work security jobs have become more popular.
